it improves users=E2=80=99 lives. =E2=80=9CHow do you link technology to va=
lue? The companies that create blue oceans always start with the value to t=
he market and work backward from there.=E2=80=9D

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09Six ways to reconstruct markets :: Companies tend to innovate in t=
he same way as their competitors because they benchmark against each other.=
 As an alternative, Mauborgne shared six ways to reshape market boundaries =
and apply blue-ocean thinking.=20

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Acros=
s industries: Look across alternative industries instead of at the competit=
ion within your own industry.=20

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Across=
 strategic groups: Look across strategic groups. =E2=80=9CInstead of focusi=
ng on a strategic group within an industry, why do people trade up and down=
 between two strategic groups?=E2=80=9D

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09Buyer group: What value would you see if you switched the buyer group?=


=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Complementary products and services:=
 =E2=80=9CWe tend to focus on only one product or service.=E2=80=9D Where a=
re there complementary products and services?

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09Functional and emotional: Can you take a functional product and ma=
ke it emotional, or vice versa? Can you switch those two within an industry=
?

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Time: Can you understand the irreve=
rsible trends in your industry, seeing analogous industries that have gone =
through those trends, and then identify how you can change value today to m=
eet that trend as it develops.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Who isn=
=E2=80=99t your customer? :: Mauborgne emphasized the idea that blue-ocean =
strategy isn=E2=80=99t about talking more with your customer; it=E2=80=
=99s about connecting with the people who are not your customers. =E2=80=
=9CWhy do they refuse your industry, refuse your product or service? What i=
s it that=E2=80=99s keeping them away? Anyone=E2=80=99s customers are just =
a drop in the bucket from the universe of non-customers.=E2=80=9D How can y=
ou convert them to become your customers?

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09The questions you should ask :: She shared two questions that members sh=
ould be asking within their organizations to help move from red to blue oce=
ans. As you plan to emerge from this crisis, ask: =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s t=
he one thing we=E2=80=99ve been doing that we could eliminate to drop our c=
ost structure?=E2=80=9D The second question should be asked not only to the=
 innovation team but to the front line. Ask: =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s the on=
e thing we should raise or create that we don=E2=80=99t offer today to meet=
 the market where it is?=E2=80=9D

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Member=
 Perspectives:

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09It=E2=80=99s interesti=
ng that some new markets that have been created have suffered the most. The=
 gig economy where companies like Airbnb or Uber don=E2=80=99t actually hav=
e or build anything; they are a facilitator.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09If you use a human-centered design process, everything should be v=
alue-based.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09We have found that you ha=
ve to improve the consumer experience in a meaningful way and also have a w=
ide moat to protect it over time to build value, which requires tech. Need =
both.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Clay Christensen=E2=80=99s job-=
to-be-done model always resonates with me, bringing people back to the prob=
lem or job being solved and away from solution or technology focus.=20

=
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Currently in our markets, the value priori=
ties are rapidly moving to safety and security.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09We ask what high-value problem a new product or service is goin=
g to address to keep value as a centerpiece of innovation.

=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09One of our biggest challenges is identifying true p=
ain points and meaningful improvements. Consumers rarely can articulate the=
ir true needs or the needs of the future, but when they see it and if it=
=E2=80=99s intuitive, they buy in quickly.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09Agree. Especially considering unarticulated needs coming from new tou=
ch points and usage occasions coming from this new normal.

=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09We are using a central group to identify shifts and=
 then having each business unit think about what it means for them. For tho=
se that are further out, we have our ventures team work it, or we have our =
corporate resources partner with the business unit.=20

=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09=09=09We have split internal (sustaining innovation) from disru=
ptive innovation and included CVC.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Se=
ems that blue ocean strategy needs big, free, open thinking as opposed to i=
nnovation in large, established companies that rely on process and =
=E2=80=9Cmeetings=E2=80=9D to help make big thinking happen at scale. Actua=
lly all a human/company transformation problem rather than an issue around =
technology or new markets.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Our centra=
l research team is meant to evaluate and identify trends that could impact =
our businesses, but then quickly support business units=E2=80=99 incorporat=
ion of change where relevant.=20

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09This q=
uestion of how do you identify the megatrends that will amplify existing bu=
sinesses, demanding shifts in how we deliver value versus those opportuniti=
es that demand incubation of fundamentally new businesses is a critical one=
.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09We are making great progress having=
 each of our business units do a forward-looking exercise on where the cons=
umer and technology is going and what the big opportunity spaces are for th=
em and then leveraging lean innovation to learn. Separate from running core=
 business but gives them access to the consumer and business knowledge that=
 arrives.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Sometimes technology breakt=
hroughs can inspire thinking about new consumer value possibilities. =20
=

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09We call this, =E2=80=9CThink big, test =
small, fail fast, learn quick.=E2=80=9D

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09My company has created an internally facing design thinking team that ha=
s developed a set of ideation and brainstorming sessions called =E2=80=
=9Cinnoventions=E2=80=9D that are used to help the core business gain clari=
ty at a very granular level around product road maps based on research, bus=
iness insights and consumer feedback.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09New technology can create entirely new uncontested spaces; what a satell=
ite will be able to do within the next five years is amazing. IP in such sp=
aces will be important.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Trusted brand=
s will matter when safety and security are top of mind.

=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Brand and reputation will matter, safety and its perce=
ption thereof, will drive growth and consumer confidence.

=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09The biggest challenge is courage to act. We are making=
 real progress starting small with lean innovation.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09=09Growing new markets is the biggest value creator. New market=
s do take time=E2=80=94so critical to keep core business healthy, too.
=

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Big businesses struggle because there a=
re a lot of processes, and those get in the way of people doing blue ocean.=
 Blue oceans aren=E2=80=99t obvious; it=E2=80=99s not more of what you do o=
r better than what you do. It=E2=80=99s doing what you don=E2=80=99t do. Pr=
ocess often gets in the way of that.=20

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09All the best practices of lean/agile innovation are true now=E2=80=94and=
 much more important than before.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09COV=
ID-19 has been an awaking for many organizations.=20

=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09=09=E2=80=9CBusiness not as usual=E2=80=9D means new pain point=
s and new opportunities.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09How to de-ri=
sk innovation. What is the human capital agenda?

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09Unfortunately in automotive, it=E2=80=99s hard to capture futur=
e optimism at this moment.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09I think th=
e concept of blue oceans is durable for decades to come. It makes me realiz=
e that execution requires courage.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09If=
 ever there was a time for humanity, this is it.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09=09Blue ocean thinking has a time and place. It=E2=80=99s not alwa=
ys conducive to actually getting innovation out the door in a timely manner=
. Moreover, if executive leadership is going to buy into this way of workin=
g, they need to have the courage and appropriate resources to execute.
=

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09What is the one thing we should stop to=
 drop our cost structure?

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Now it=
=E2=80=99s about not =E2=80=9Cboiling the ocean=E2=80=9D too quickly.

=
=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Non-disruptive creations=E2=80=94I like th=
e word choice.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Value innovation is un=
derstanding what people will pay for, and we see many of the value-creating=
 attributes that drove disruptors like Airbnb might migrate back to those w=
ho were disrupted (e.g., traditional hotels).

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=
=09=09=09Make your core businesses better and aggressively capture value fr=
om new opportunities.

=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09=09Emphasis on val=
ue creation aspect of innovation. Stimulated thinking on coordination to br=
ing in different voices and extract customer value.

