i><strong>The ultimate intersection ::&nbsp;</strong>What common thread run=
s through the many geniuses Isaacson has studied? They=E2=80=99re all imagi=
native, creative and innovative=E2=80=94and multidisciplinary. =E2=80=9CThe=
y all stood at the intersection of the arts and sciences,=E2=80=9D he said,=
 and they could see patterns across different disciplines. Steve Jobs would=
 say that creativity occurs when you stand at the intersection of art and t=
echnology. The other key trait they have in common? They had a =E2=80=9Cwil=
d curiosity for its own sake.=E2=80=9D They were all passionately inquisiti=
ve about anything and everything; they had =E2=80=9Cthe driven curiosity to=
 stop and observe things.=E2=80=9D</li>
=09<li><strong>Simplicity in desi=
gn ::&nbsp;</strong>While most people think of design as a surface attribut=
e, da Vinci and Jobs knew that =E2=80=9Cthe essence of great design meant y=
ou had to go below the surface.=E2=80=9D They believed that =E2=80=9Csimpli=
city is the ultimate sophistication.=E2=80=9D Thus, to achieve simplicity a=
nd beautiful design, you must fully understand the complexity beneath it. D=
a Vinci studied the complex inner workings of the human body in order to pa=
int the beautiful, seemingly simple smile of<em>&nbsp;Mona Lisa</em>. Jobs =
iterated over and over again in order to achieve the intuitive, sleek desig=
n of the iPhone</li>
=09<li><strong>The physical and the digital ::&nbsp;=
</strong>The pandemic launched a massive experiment in remote work, and exe=
cutives are now charged with leading their organizations=E2=80=99 reopening=
 plans. Isaacson noted that Jobs was fanatical about creating opportunities=
 for people to meet in real life. Apple headquarters=E2=80=99 unique ring s=
hape was designed to create moments for employees to meet spontaneously. He=
 believed that bumping into each other would serendipitously spark new idea=
s. In the post-COVID-19 world, we=E2=80=99ll have to figure out how to bala=
nce physical and digital experiences to get the best from both.</li>
=09<=
li><strong>A source of optimism ::&nbsp;</strong>While every issue is immed=
iately polarized even amid a global crisis, Isaacson shared what gives him =
optimism for the future: Gen Z, whom he believes might be better called the=
 Corona Generation. His students have been very engaged in helping the comm=
unity around them. COVID-19 is shaping this generation. =E2=80=9CThey=
=E2=80=99re feeling that they=E2=80=99re all in this together as a new gene=
ration.=E2=80=9D He=E2=80=99s hopeful that in the future, when facing anoth=
er major crisis, =E2=80=9Cthat they will be less bitter and partisan and di=
visive than we are when they attack and approach social and civic issues.=
=E2=80=9D</li>
