<ul>
=09<li><strong>Leading in the current crisis ::&nbsp;</strong>=
The pandemic has been a major global shock, and companies will be impacted =
differently by industry and geography. =E2=80=9CThis is an invitation for a=
ll of us to have our finest hour,=E2=80=9D said Joly. Supply chains will li=
kely be reconfigured, and the era of unlimited globalization has ended. The=
 relationships between business, governments and society will evolve. Many =
companies won=E2=80=99t just have to restart; they=E2=80=99ll have to reset=
. The world is moving into a new era, =E2=80=9Cbut nobody has a script.=
=E2=80=9D Leaders must use resilience and agility to prepare for and naviga=
te this new normal.</li>
=09<li><strong>Purpose and humanity ::&nbsp;</st=
rong>Many of the principles Joly relied on while leading Best Buy=E2=80=
=99s turnaround are applicable for executives steering their organizations =
through the COVID-19 crisis. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s the idea of putting peop=
le and customers first, and treating profit as an outcome as opposed to the=
 main goal.=E2=80=9D Navigating an organization through crisis requires lea=
ding with both purpose and humanity. When leaders use purpose as a lens, th=
ey move from dangerous zero-sum games and begin to see new possibilities an=
